<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n33306c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33306c">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33306c"> 306(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hipbasket / staminate pollen / stigma</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">THE HUMBLE-BEE. The neuter bees are also deputed to considerable work in obtaining supplies; and <font color="green">[141]</font> with the rising of the sun they sally forth to meet the opening flower at dawn, suck from the corolla whatever honey it may afford, and fill their little <mark>hip-baskets</mark> with bee-bread. Hopping, skipping, and flying from flower to flower they act as fertilizers, bearing the <mark>staminate pollen</mark> of one plant to the <mark>stigma</mark> of another. <small> J.H. Crabtree, <a name="JHCW" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JHCW"><cite title="source">Wonders of Insect Life</cite></a> (n.d.) 141-2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The sigma is the receptive surface of a flower. </mm> </dd></dl>
